Modeling and prediction for movies

Introduction

As part of the Linear Regression and Modeling course, the final task is to prepare and submit a data analysis project. The data analysis project is involving dataset information from Rotten Tomatoes and IMDB for a random sample of movies.

The task is to identify the attributes that make a movie popular. In the same time to learn new things about movies.

The data should allow us to generalize to the population of interest. However, there is no causation can be established because random assignment is not used in this study. In addition, potential biases are associated with non-voting or non_rating because the voting and rating are voluntary on IMDB and Rotten Tomatoes website.

Part 2: Research question

This data analysis project is to study the attributes that contributes to the popularity of a movie.

The following information in the dataset will be explore in the next section in order to understand the popularity of a movies:-
  1. title_type: Type of movie (Documentary, Feature Film, TV Movie)
  2. genre: Genre of movie (Action & Adventure, Comedy, Documentary, Drama, Horror, Mystery & Suspense, Other)
  3. runtime: Runtime of movie (in minutes)
  4. imdb_rating: Rating on IMDB
  5. imdb_num_votes: Number of votes on IMDB
  6. critics_rating: Categorical variable for critics rating on Rotten Tomatoes (Certified Fresh, Fresh, Rotten)
  8. critics_score: Critics score on Rotten Tomatoes
  9. audience_rating: Categorical variable for audience rating on Rotten Tomatoes (Spilled, Upright)
  10. audience_score: Audience score on Rotten Tomatoes
  11. best_pic_win: Whether or not the movie won a best picture Oscar (no, yes)
  12. best_actor_win: Whether or not one of the main actors in the movie ever won an Oscar (no, yes) - note that this is not necessarily whether the actor won an Oscar for their role in the given movie
  13. best_actress win: Whether or not one of the main actresses in the movie ever won an Oscar (no, yes) - not that this is not necessarily whether the actresses won an Oscar for their role in the given movie
  14. best_dir_win: Whether or not the director of the movie ever won an Oscar (no, yes) - not that this is not necessarily whether the director won an Oscar for the given movie

distribution<-function(var){
  ggplot(movies, aes(x=var)) + 
  geom_histogram(aes(y=..density..), colour="black", fill="white")+
  geom_density(alpha=.2, fill="#FF6666")+
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept=mean(var)),
             color="blue", linetype="dashed", size=1)+
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept=median(var)),
             color="red", linetype="dashed", size=1)+
  ylab("Density")+
  labs(caption="Note: Red/Blue vertical line marks the median/mean value.
       The histogram is overlaid with the density plot.")+
  theme_minimal()
}

Part 4: Modeling

We fit a multiple linear regression model with imdb_rating as the response variable, and title_type, runtime, critics_rating, critics_score, audience_rating, audience_score and best_pic_win as predictors. Regression result is shown in the first column in the following table.

The coefficient of best_pic_win is not significant, therefore we exclude this variable based on backwards elimination (p-value). The new regression result is in the second column. The coefficients of the remaining variables as well as the models adjusted R-squared do not change too much.

OLS1<-lm(imdb_rating ~ title_type+runtime+critics_rating+
          critics_score+audience_rating+audience_score+best_pic_win,data = movies)
OLS2<-lm(imdb_rating ~ title_type+runtime+critics_rating+
          critics_score+audience_rating+audience_score,data = movies)
stargazer(OLS1,OLS2,type='text')

Normally distributed error terms

The QQ plot shows that the error terms are almost normally distributed.

qqnorm(OLS2$residuals)
qqline(OLS2$residuals)

Homoskedasticity

A particularly small p-value as the result of the Breush-Pagan test implies that the null hypothesis of homoskedasiticity is rejected. There is, indeed, heteroskedasticity in our model.

lmtest::bptest(OLS2)
## 
##  studentized Breusch-Pagan test
## 
## data:  OLS2
## BP = 92.225, df = 8, p-value < 2.2e-16

No autocorrelation

Finally, a large p-value of the Durbin-Watson test indicates that there is no autocorrelation.

lmtest::dwtest(OLS2)
## 
##  Durbin-Watson test
## 
## data:  OLS2
## DW = 1.9483, p-value = 0.2551
## alternative hypothesis: true autocorrelation is greater than 0
Therefore, the interpretation coefficient of the categorical variables and the numeric variables are as follow:-
  1. All else held equal, compared to a documentary, a feature film scores 0.165 lower in IMDB rating.
  2. All else held equal, 1 point increase in audience rating leads to 0.041 points increase in IMDB rating.

Part 5: Prediction

Finally, in this section we will pick three (3) movies, from the Rotten Tomatoes to make prediction of its rating in IMDB. The following movies is selected with the Rotten Tomatoes predictions respectively:-
  1. Movie: Project Power, Critic score: 60%, Audience score: 51% & runtime: 111 min
  2. Movie: Host, Critic score: 100%, Audience score: 76% & runtime: 56 min
  3. Movie: Time Trap, Critic score: 64%, Audience score: 67% & runtime: 87 min 
new_movie<-data.frame(title_type="Feature Film", runtime=111, critics_rating="Certified Fresh",critics_score=61, audience_rating="Spilled",audience_score=52)
predicted<-predict(OLS2,new_movie)
interval<-predict(OLS2,new_movie,interval = "prediction", level = 0.95)
print(paste("The predicted IMDB rating for Project Power is", predicted))
## [1] "The predicted IMDB rating for Project Power is 6.2064688523883"
print(paste("The lower bound of the 95% prediction interval is",interval[2]))
## [1] "The lower bound of the 95% prediction interval is 5.28689402134422"
print(paste("The upper bound of the 95% prediction interval is",interval[3]))
## [1] "The upper bound of the 95% prediction interval is 7.12604368343237"
new_movie<-data.frame(title_type="Feature Film", runtime=56, critics_rating="Certified Fresh",critics_score=100, audience_rating="Spilled",audience_score=76)

Based on the model predictions, the results are as follow:-
  1. Movie: Project Power IMDB rating is 6.2 with est, range of 5.2 to 7.1
  2. Movie: Host IMDB rating is 7.5 with est, range of 6.5 to 8.4
  3. Movie: Time Trap IMDB rating is 6.7 with est, range of 5.8 to 7.7

Part 6: Conclusion

In this project, we explore the factors that affect the IMDB rating of a movie and summarised as follow:-
  1. By using the multiple linear regression, the runtime, critics score and audience score are positively correlated with a higher movie rating.
  2. All else held equal, compared to documentaries, feature movies and TV movies tend to score lower.
  3. All else held equal, compared to a movie rated as spilled, an upright movie has a lower score.
  4. The prediction IMDB rating for Project Power is 6.2% but actual is 6.0. This shows the prediction accuracy is about 97% and within the prediction range of 5.2% to 7.1%
  5. The prediction IMDB rating for Host is 7.5% but actual is 6.7. This shows the prediction accuracy is about 89% and within the prediction range of 6.5% to 8.4%
  6. The prediction IMDB rating for Time Trap is 6.7% but actual is 6.3. This shows the prediction accuracy is about 95% and within the prediction range of 5.8% to 7.7%
